field_label: 11. Why did you choose this number?
11. Why did you choose this number?
value_text:
Some fields lack customization, for example the ranking, which requires sorting through all the options, whereas we would like to have a minimum and maximum number of options to choose from.
On some fields (e.g. matrix), the ‚ÄúBulk Edit‚Äù option is missing. 
We would like the possibility to indicate the number of question (and the progression "{current} / {total}"

field_label: 11. Why did you choose this number?
value_text: We've been using Formbricks for almost 2 years now and it's helped our UX team a lot!

field_label: 11. Why did you choose this number?
value_text: best solution I've found so far at good price

field_label: 2. Can you share with us how we helped to solve your problems?
value_text: We use Formbricks to automatically collect feedback From customers after different kinds of interactions (after visiting a store - we are a retailer -, contacting our customer service, etc.). We use te API to create unique invite links and to pull responses. Webhooks are used to trigger follow-up actions (e.g. issue a reward).

field_label: 2. Can you share with us how we helped to solve your problems?
value_text: We chose Formbricks in 2024 for its open-source nature. We use it occasionally (once a year) to collect feedback from users of our application.

field_label: 2. Can you share with us how we helped to solve your problems?
value_text: Simple way to toss up "sign up" surveys, "interest in X" surveys.  Plan at some point to add a "give feedback" button.

field_label: 2. Can you share with us how we helped to solve your problems?
value_text: I've been in contact with Johannes regarding some issues with the React Native SDK. This resulted in a quick workaround and the issue being prioritized for an upcoming SDK release.

field_label: 2. Can you share with us how we helped to solve your problems?
2. Can you share with us how we helped to solve your problems?
value_text: I can find good templates and get good data

field_label: 3. Can you share with us how we can help to solve your problems better?
value_text:
- crank up the performance, loading of a survey list is now very slow
- allow to download data from multiple surveys in one file

field_label: 3. Can you share with us how we can help to solve your problems better?
value_text: We are a bit special in that regard. Due to e2ee promise we can‚Äôt include arbitrary js snippets from third parties. hence we had to remove or not even include in some parts of our apps.

field_label: 3. Can you share with us how we can help to solve your problems better?
value_text: Have a view whete I can see each answer, not just the cumulate answers.

field_label: 3. Can you share with us how we can help to solve your problems better?
value_text: I like formbricks so far but it could use so work on viewing the survey results

field_label: 4. What's the ONE feature you are missing at Formbricks? Why?
value_text: easy integration of forms via npm i and forwarding the responses via our backend, not directly from frontend. but again, i guess this won‚Äôt be relevant for a lot of other customers

field_label: 4. What's the ONE feature you are missing at Formbricks? Why?
value_text: Be able to hide a question without having to isolate it in a dedicated block

field_label: 4. What's the ONE feature you are missing at Formbricks? Why?
value_text: App log-in token only lasts 1 day!  Each day I want to check status of an ongoing survey, I need to log in again!

field_label: 4. What's the ONE feature you are missing at Formbricks? Why?
4. What's the ONE feature you are missing at Formbricks? Why?
value_text: Better results viewing... Individual viewing and final results in a clean way. I am used to using google forms so this is an upgrade overall but I like how I was able to view results on that platform better than Formbricks.

field_label: 4. What's the ONE feature you are missing at Formbricks? Why?
value_text:
We would like to have the option of filtering survey responses by segments and not individual attributes.
Based on filtering by segment, we would like to be able to compare survey responses by segment/and or other attributes.
Breakdown charts, pie charts and more would also be super helpful for our UX team.

field_label: 4. What's the ONE feature you are missing at Formbricks? Why?
value_text: I liked the custom redirect URL for the final button at the end of the survey (this functionality was deprecated from the free plan recently)

field_label: 4. What's the ONE feature you are missing at Formbricks? Why?

11. What integrations are you missing?
value_text:
While Zapier support is a great start, it would be really valuable to see more native integrations, especially with popular tools like:

ActiveCampaign for example, to match survey answers to an existing contact (via email) and update custom fields.

Notion: the ability to search for an existing item (e.g. based on email) and then update or append answers to a card/property in a database.

These kinds of direct integrations would allow smoother, faster automation, without relying on third-party tools. Especially for teams who use surveys to qualify leads or update CRM records.

field_label: 4. What is ONE thing we could improve for you?
4. What is ONE thing we could improve for you?
value_text:
When a respondent selects an answer on a single select question (e.g. multiple choice with only one allowed option), it would be great if the survey automatically advanced to the next question without requiring an extra click on ‚ÄúNext‚Äù.

This would make the flow much faster and smoother, especially on mobile. It‚Äôs a common pattern in modern survey tools like Typeform and Tally, and it significantly improves completion rates.

Ideally, this could be:

Enabled by default for single select questions

Or offered as a toggle in the question settings (e.g. ‚ÄúAuto-advance when option is selected‚Äù)

field_label: 4. What is ONE thing we could improve for you?
value_text:
Consistency and reliability during survey edits.  Specifically the use of variables 

For example, in the editor:  

If I enter a question "How likely is it first_name will attend event_name on event_date?" to get the variables I have to type @ for teh drop down each time in sequence as I enter  the question.  But, if I go back and try to edit the question, e.g. "How likely is it first_name last_name will attend event_name on event_date?" then: 

Firstly: I can't go back and edit the question at the point at whicnh I want to instert the additional variable - i.e. insterting @ doesn't bring up the list of variables.  Instead I have to erase the rest of the question and re-type it from scratch from that point.

Secondly: a lot of the time Formbricks dumps the other variables as soon as the question is edited, and I end up with "How likely is it @first_name last_name will attend @event_name on @event_date?" 

When trying to use the variables in a URL,  Formbricks doesn't consistently work.  For example this URL construction only correctly populates the first_name and ignores the other fields, for no obvious reason: 
https://app.formbricks.com/s/surveyID?first_name=Abbie&last_name=Cook&sent_to_email=emailtest1%40domain.com&competition_name=London%20Open%202025&competition_display_date=8-9%20Mar%202025&Question1ID=Yes&startAt=Question2ID&skipPrefilled=true

field_label: 4. What is ONE thing we could improve for you?
value_text: One area where Formbricks could improve is by expanding its documentation and user guides. While the platform offers a powerful open-source form builder, some users may find it challenging to navigate more advanced features like complex logic or custom integrations without detailed, step-by-step instructions. Improving the clarity and depth of documentation would enhance user experience, especially for beginners or those with limited technical expertise. Better guides could help users unlock the full potential of Formbricks more easily
